Response ID: resp_4121
Response Text: After the previous restructure, my arts organization has no longer been awarded any funding from the cultural contracts. The feedback is utterly inconsistent from the panels who have evaluated our applications. I devoted countless hours for nothing when my organization had previously funded fora  decade in which we turned small awards into incredible, critically acclaimed and award-winning productions. As far the theatre community goes, Austin cultural landscape feels post-apocalyptic. The funding restructure quite literally gutted the cultural ecosystem. So many artists left town, quit making work, or keep trying to begin again to no avail. There must be some way to restore some funding to artists whose missions are simply to make beautiful, transformative and relevant performance. The prescribed pursuit of serving exclusively communities experiencing "the threat of erasure" is wholly limiting, short-sited, and has proven to damage and penalize the very communities the restructure sought to serve. In the future, it might be better to listen to the community instead of hiring out-of-town consultant who know nothing about the incredible network of artists that made this a vibrant and interesting place to live.

